<p>I recently started learning D3.js because I am interested in data visualization. Hence I ask you to be patient because (beside a MOOC on Udacity) I am a beginner (and a quite untalented one).</p>  <p>My goal is to create a map of Italy whose regions will deform (shrink or enlarge) depending on my data. However, I am stuck at the very beginning of the project: drawing the map.</p>  <p>I uploaded everything to a <a href="https://github.com/Federicopvs/quars.git" rel="nofollow">github repository</a>. The json file to draw the map is italy_regions.json; while the html file is basic.html.</p>  <pre><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; &lt;html&gt; &lt;head&gt; &lt;meta charset="utf-8"&gt; &lt;script src="http://d3js.org/d3.v3.min.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt; &lt;style&gt; &lt;/style&gt; &lt;script type="text/javascript"&gt;     function draw(geo_data) {         "use strict";         var margin = 75,             width = 1400,             height = 600;          var svg = d3.select("body")             .append("svg")             .attr("width", width - margin)             .attr("height", height - margin)             .append('g')             .attr('class', 'map');          var projection = d3.geo.mercator()                             .scale(150)                             .translate( [width / 2, height / 2]);          var path = d3.geo.path().projection(projection);          var map = svg.selectAll('path')                     .data(geo_data.features)                     .enter()                     .append('path')                     .attr('d', path)                     .style('fill', 'lightBlue')                     .style('stroke', 'black')                     .style('stroke-width', 0.5);     };  &lt;/script&gt; &lt;/head&gt; &lt;body&gt; &lt;script type="text/javascript"&gt;  d3.json("italy_regions.topojson", draw);  &lt;/script&gt; &lt;/body&gt; &lt;/html&gt; </code></pre>  <p>The code is adapted directly from a lesson of the MOOC. If I set the scale to 150 the map is (sort of) centered but very small. As I increase the scale, the map becomes a bit bigger but its center moves, so that after a certain point it disappears from the map. If I use another map (world_countries.json) the map centers and scales as expected.</p>  <p>I don't understand if this is an issue of the json file used to draw the map or f I do not understand the workings of the translate and scale functions. Could you please shed some light on my doubts or point to some source where I can learn more about this?</p>  <p>Thanks a lot!</p>  <p>Fede</p>